w York","organization":"State of New York","start_year":1821,"end_year":1829}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["law","politics"],"notable_blurb":"Attorney General of New York","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_A._Talcott","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"law","header":"He beat Daniel Webster at the Supreme Court","body":"Arguing a landmark trusts-and-perpetuities case before the U.S. Supreme Court, Talcott prevailed against Daniel Webster himself. The dispute, over the Sailors' Snug Harbor estate, was a stage few country-trained lawyers ever reached. The victory sealed his standing among the era's great advocates."},{"number":2,"category":"politics","header":"Eight years as New York's attorney general","body":"Appointed attorney general of New York in 1821, Talcott held the office for eight years. He was a leading member of the Albany Regency, the machine that ran the state for the Van Buren faction. Few lawyers argued more often before its highest courts."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"From a country office to the front rank","body":"Talcott studied law in the office of Gold and Sill and was admitted to the bar in 1812. He built his practice outward from Lowville to Utica before reaching New York City. Within a decade he stood among the most respected advocates in the state."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"Forced out for “irregular habits”","body":"In 1829 Talcott resigned the attorney generalship under the phrase “irregular habits.” It was the period's polite euphemism for a drinking problem. The brilliance of his public career ran alongside that private struggle."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"The bar said his learning was never surpassed","body":"At his death the New York Bar gathered to mourn him in the Supreme Court chamber. Its resolution praised talent and scholarship “rarely equaled and never surpassed” at the bar of the state. He was forty-six."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM056"},"slug":"samuel-austin-talcott-1789"},"T02292":{"id":"T02292","bio":{"first_name":"Child","last_name":"Talcott","display_name":"Child Talcott"},"gender":"unknown","birth":{"year":1777,"date_precision":"approximate"},"death":{"year":1778},"parents":{"father_id":"T00394","mother_id":"U00066"},"marriages":[],"classification":{"is_talcott_descendant":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":5,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false},"tags":["died_young","died_in_infancy"],"slug":"child-talcott-1777"},"T02293":{"id":"T02293","bio":{"first_name":"Infant","last_name":"Talcott","display_name":"Infant Talcott"},"gender":"unknown","birth":{"year":1788,"date_precision":"approximate"},"death":{"year":1789},"parents":{"father_id":"T00394","mother_id":"U00066"},"marriages":[],"classification":{"is_talcott_descendant":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":5,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false},"tags":["died_young","died_in_infancy"],"slug":"infant-talcott-1788"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM056","name":"Old North Cemetery","city":"Hartford","county":"Hartford County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","lat":41.7712,"lng":-72.6832,"visitable":true,"hooker_connections":["H00792","HD1329","HD1330","HD1331","HD2619","HD4160","HD4167","HD4171","I00626","I00628","H00107","H00546","I00297","I00298","H01467","T00394","U00066","T02291"],"sources":[]},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}